title: For Sale/Trade:  Marlin model 1895 Cowboy 45/70, JM marked barrel!
postcontent:
Up for sale is my Marlin model 1895 Cowboy Action 45/70.  It has a 26" octagon barrel, and is JM stamped; which means it was made by Marlin before Remington bought them out and ruined the quality control of these guns.  According to the serial number it was made in 2002.  (serial  number begins with the digits 982)  The gun was bought in '02 or '03 by its original owner at a local gun store here in Indianapolis.  He told me that he fired around 15 or 20 (modern, not black powder) rounds through it and put it up for the last 10 years.  I believe him, considering the condition the rifle is in.  It is in 100% perfect mechanical condition, but it has a couple of minor flaws in the finish.  On both the left and right side of the barrel about 8" from the muzzle the bluing is thin.  It looks like a factory blemish to me, but could be from long term storage.  There is no rust or pitting, just a couple of spots that are lighter than the rest of the gun.  If I didn't tell you about them it would probably take awhile for you to notice.  The gun cycles as smooth as butter, and the trigger pull is very crisp and light.  It is overall a beautiful gun.  Definitely heirloom quality.  The only reason I am selling it is because I know it will get scratched up if I keep it, since I am rough on my rifles.  I really don't want to do that to such a good looking gun, so I would rather get something that is more modern that wont bother me when it gets scratched up.  I am not willing to ship the rifle at this time, so sales and trades are face to face only.

Text me at 317-529-seven two nine nine.

Straight blowback action offers enhanced simplicity and reliability while a polished feed ramp offers reliable feeding with all types of rimfire ammo. The 4.25" stainless steel barrel of the 1911-22 A1 is target crowned and the aluminum frame is machined to exacting tolerances. Vertical serrations on the slide provide an improved cocking grip, and the manual slide release is easily operated with the shooting or support hand. It has a large manual thumb safety and grip safety. The 10-round steel magazine body is heat treated for long-term feeding reliability and long life with the magazine release positioned adjacent to the trigger guard for convenient operation.

Each pistol made and retailed by Browning during the first year of production will include a collector’s certificate of authenticity as well as a commemorative canvas/leather zippered pistol case.

title: For Sale:  Springfield 1911 EMP 9mm 3" 10RD Package
postcontent:
1 year old EMP with 500 rounds through it.  Love this gun.  It fits awesome in the hand, very accurate, and a future collector's item.  Only reason I am selling is that I need to add to my preps and have a couple extra guns to sell to fund it.

The Springfield Armory 9mm Enhanced Micro Pistol (EMP) is the 
first production 1911 made from the ground up to shoot short 
cartridges like 9mm, 40 S&W and 45 GAP. The result? The smallest, 
most concealable 1911 you can buy.

Previously, when 1911s were chambered for short-action calibers like the 
9mm, 40 S&W and 45 GAP, this was done on guns built around the 
longer 45 ACP cartridge (Essentially, long-action 1911s). Spacers 
were placed in the magazine to align the shorter cartridges. The EMP 
is the first production 1911 designed specifically for these shorter 
cartridges.

The world got its first glimpse of the short-action 1911 in 2005 with a 
prototype Springfield gun called the "Defender." Chambered in 45 
GAP, this rare gun received rave reviews from numerous firearms 
publications. We decided to launch this new class of 1911 in the more popular 9mm caliber in the EMP.

title: For Sale:  Daewoo DR-200
postcontent:
For Sale: Daewoo DR-200 

If you're tired of the same-old AR platform that everyone else has and are looking for something a bit different then check this out. This gun is basically the love child of an AR, AK and FAL. Uses FAL adjustable gas system, AK style gas piston and AR style bolt/FCG. Uses normal AR STANAG magazine (e.g. GI mags, PMags, etc). These guns are super reliable.

These were imported by Kimber in the 90s (lower is stamped 'Kimber'). They had hideous thumbhole stocks and ugly handguards. I converted to use adjustable M4 style stock and TuffForce FAL handguard. Also put on a StormWerkz optic rail. These guns are floating around out there but you're not likely to see very many. Only time I've ever seen another one in person was in the hands of a 14 year old Guatemalan military soldier when I was in Guatemala earlier this year. I noticed it, yelled "Daewoo?" and he raised the gun in the air and gave me a thumbs up.

Anyway, I'm asking $1,250 firm for this. Located in Lawrence/Maury County and will not travel far.

title: For Sale:  Russian 1917 Tula M91 Mosin-Nagant rifle w/extras
location: Grey Forest (NW of SA), San Antonio, Texas
postcontent:
Here is a beautiful old Russian M91 rifle, all the way from 1917. This one is of particular interest to collectors because of its date and markings. Anyone with an interest in Russia will recognize 1917 as the start of the Bolshevik Revolution. Although this weapon is marked as having been manufactured at the "Tula Emporer Peter the Great Ordinance Factory", it lacks the Imperial crest that normally accompanied such markings. I do not claim to know for sure, but given the date and markings, I think it's likely that this weapon was in production and had already been marked when the fun began, but was only completed and allowed to leave the plant after the crest was removed by the "Workers". See an example of the complete mark – 62x54r.net/MosinID/MosinTheOp.htm#MarkChanges – and compare it to the pictures below.

Such speculation aside, what I can see for sure is a complete, historically correct example of this model, in very good overall condition. It does have a few dings and scratches, as would be expected from a nearly-100-year-old weapon. The stock is beautiful wood with brass appointments, all finished in what I believe to be the original factory shellac. The metal retains most of the original factory finish. The weapon has the desirable hexagonal receiver. Serial numbers on the barrel, buttplate and receiver all match, though those on the bolt and floorplate do not.

The sale includes the original canvas sling with leather and metal hardware, the original cleaning rod, and a detachable bayonet of the correct type. Not included in this deal is a supply of various ammunition for this caliber, which I will detail and offer first to the buyer, at a reasonable price to be negotiated. If the buyer of the rifle does not want the ammunition, I will list it separately after the rifle sells.

I am not a gunsmith nor an expert on these weapons, but I have inspected the weapon and researched its history, and have described it to the best of my ability. I will be happy to answer any questions, and I will be happy to provide better or additional pictures if desired. It should go without saying that this rifle is old stock, and may not be as reliable as a modern, recently-produced weapon. Although my inspection reveals no apparent problems, you assume all risk of its use should you decide to attempt to fire it – so I urge the purchaser to have the weapon inspected by a competent gunsmith.

I prefer a face-to-face deal for cash somewhere in the Northwest San Antonio area, but I am willing to ship if necessary, at your expense. As this is a complete functioning weapon, it must be shipped to a licensed dealer in your vicinity, whose services you must arrange and pay for. Shipping will be at cost, via UPS. All told, it's about 12 pounds boxed up.

As this weapon now has potentially winning bids on its auction on Gunbroker, it is no longer available for sale here. If you would be interested in purchasing it, I encourage you to bid on it via Gunbroker -- www.gunbroker.com/Auction/ViewItem.aspx?Item=367918450

title: For Sale:  Price dropped. H&R 22 Special (mod 922) top-break, 9 shot .22
location: anywhere in middle TN, Nashville, Tennessee
postcontent:
This revolver is actually an antique (manufactured late 1930's) but I chose to list in under handguns because it is a fun, functional shooter. I bought this gun about a year ago because I thought it was cool, but also because it was accurate plinker that could be used to shoot Aguilla Colibri and super Colibri rounds, which are quieter than a nail gun out of this 6" barreled handgun. I'm not claiming to have done any plinking inside city limits, but if I had the neighbors would've been none the wiser ;)

In it's day, this double action, fast reloading, 9 shot revolver could have been a respectable defensive sidearm, especially with it's light weight and slim profile. Of course today you would be crazy to choose this as a carry gun, but it is fun to shoot and beautiful with it's excellent condition wood "saw-handle" grips and Webley-like top break action. It has a crisp, precise sight picture with the brass front sight blade. Sights are non-adjustable and dead on at the short distances I've shot it.

I've enjoyed this gun but have been unemployed for two months and really need some extra cash for necessities. It's been thoroughly cleaned and is in good condition. Does have some holster wear at end of barrell and front edge of cylinder from the original owner, but there is no corrosion. Will sell for $275.
